snippet.textDisplay: Another silly episode with a silly doctor.  Sorry, but I can't say if it's due to the writing, directing or casting, I'll never warm up to this new Doctor and set of companions.  It doesn't feel like Doctor Who.  The only thing Doctor Who about it is the TARDIS.  That's about it.  They should have just created a new series featuring a female Time Lord instead of the stunt casting of changing the gender of The Doctor. The season 12 episode was so bad.  They're all stealing motor scooters, driving over dirt, every bullet fired at them is only hitting the front of the bikes no matter where the car is.  Then they literally chase down a taxing plane to catch a guy who mysteriously isn't in the cockpit anymore.  Dumb plot devices to get everyone on a plane so they can do a dumb reveal.

snippet.textDisplay:
Think some of the fans below are right to be guarded in their optimism. Don't forget that Chibnall's earlier stories included cramming everything but the kitchen sink in, before trying to answer it all in the final 10 minutes (see '42' and 'The Power of Three', not to mention the cop-outs in S11 like 'The Ghost Monument'). This could be similar. I am nervous that with a two-parter, instead of using pacing in the second half to answer the most intriguing questions, we will get a lot more flash and action and then a shoddy £1-shop bow which barely ties anything up. And don't forget - the only thing S11 did bring to Dr. Who is the mystery of the 'Timeless Child'... if that doesn't get answered in S12, I may cry. BUT, I have hope. I liked this - still kinda clunky in plot (don't let the chases distract you - we've seen world domination countless times), but a good ol'fashioned sci-fi romp.

Sidenote: I'd love it if those aliens were 'The Boneless' from Flatline. But the callback to Tissue Compression makes me think it'll be a long-forgotten classic villain being resurrected by the Master.

Side-sidenote: Sacha's performance here was incredible to me, albeit sudden, in the last few mins. Definitely Simm 2.0 but if they just acknowledge the canon for 2 seconds and give him a bit more depth, he has the makings of a brilliant Master. These companions better finish part 2 with a working knowledge of the Master because they don't seem to know anything about the Doctor and this just adds to it!

snippet.textDisplay: One episode in. And it's so, so much better than last season. Those odd aliens - I was thinking that they might be Vardans, from 'The Invasion Of Time' - they travel along any energy wavelength. But then, as they surrounded 'O's house/Master's TARDIS, it reminded me of the Gellguards from 'The Three Doctors', which were anti-matter creatures from the anti-matter universe of Omega, which, when I saw that odd 'jungle', made me think of the story 'Planet Of Evil', which features the jungle planet Zeta Minor, on the very edge of the known universe, and which is a gateway to an anti-matter universe. Every time that anti-matter has featured on Doctor Who, it has been an undetectible threat. I'm going on a limb here, and saying that the lost and completely insane Time Lord engineer Omega is trying to enter the matter universe again. I was pleased to hear mention of The Master's TCE (Tissue Compression Eliminator) again - but I thought that it was destroyed on Sarn by The Doctor's Fifth Incarnation, after he killed shapeshifting robot Kamelion with it.

snippet.textDisplay: I think there’s a strong possibility this is john Simms master really. They openly state that O is a real person and that the master currently has O’s face as a fake identity hence the matchbox that’s has the real o inside it. We didn’t see John Simms master actually regenerate so he could’ve got to his tardis in time, but there’s still a possibility that he might have regenerated into someone else that we’ve not seen yet. It’s definitely not Missy’s next regeneration because she turned good. Plus with Missy’s death it feels like Moffat has essentially written future incarnations beyond missy into a corner.
